"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627332","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-16","<p>Carriers who transport companion animals, such as pet cats and dogs, are obliged to meet the requirements of Council Regulation (EC) No 1/2005 on the protection of animals during transport. This Regulation requires commercial carriers, such as the ferry company DFDS, to be authorised as an animal transporter. Authorised transporters must ensure that staff are trained and must have procedures and operating instructions in place that demonstrate compliance with the Regulation.</p><p>In addition, in England, we also expect ferry companies to take into account the requirements of The Code of Practice for the Welfare of Dogs and the Code of Practice for the Welfare of Cats when transporting cats and dogs in order to meet their welfare needs in accordance with the Animal Welfare Act 2006.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-16T17:50:32.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627332/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627332/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","DFDS: Ferries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of whether the requirement of the ferry company DFDS to require companion animals such as dogs and cats to remain inside vehicles and unattended during ferry crossings is compliant with her Department's pet travel policies.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","51554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627333","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Calderdale Flood Action Plan is a partnership plan and Natural England has the lead responsibility for policy 62.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England has a duty under the Habitat Regulations to review any consents/permissions which were issued prior to designation as a European Site. Previously there was discretion as to whether the activities covered by the consents could be tackled through incentives and/or advice rather than formally affirming, modifying or revoking the consent. This discretionary aspect has been removed and under the 2012 amendment of the Habitats Regulations 2010 (Section 23) Natural England now has the legal duty to affirm, modify or revoke any consents issued on European sites, as soon as reasonably practicable.</p><p> </p><p>As part of an England-wide strategy to restore blanket bog to Favourable Conservation Status, Natural England is currently reviewing all consents on blanket bog in line with the duty above (including those which permit burning) and working with landowners to put in place sustainable management and use of these sensitive areas. This will include completing the necessary programme of capital works such as grip-blocking to restore the natural hydrology of the bog and seeding/planting of peat-forming species such as cotton grasses and sphagnum mosses.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-07T13:56:41.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627333/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627333/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Flood Control: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to policy 62 of the Calderdale Flood Action Plan, published in October 2016, for what reasons the Environment Agency will progressively review existing burning consents with regard to moorland in Calderdale.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","51681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627334","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-08","<p>No Minister will be attending the 13<sup>th</sup> Conference of the Parties to the Convention on Biological Diversity. From September to December 2016 there will be four major global meetings to discuss biodiversity conservation. It is not always possible to arrange Ministerial attendance at all meetings and difficult decisions have to be made.</p><p>The Government takes biodiversity loss very seriously, as demonstrated by my attendance at the recent CITES meeting in Johannesburg and the Secretary of State’s planned attendance at the Hanoi Conference on the Illegal Wildlife Trade. Defra and the UK will continue to have a strong influence on this agenda.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-08T12:04:36.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627334/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627334/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","UN Convention on Biological Diversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which Minister from her Department plans to attend the 13th Conference of the Parties to the Convention on Biological Diversity in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","51657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627335","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Department for International Trade is the lead department on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) and has established a process for regular cross-Whitehall engagement with relevant parts of Government, including Defra, to ensure matters arising from the TTIP discussions have been considered appropriately.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","51638 ; 51642","2016-11-10T15:31:17.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627335/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627335/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Environment Agency on the implications for its remit of the draft Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","51647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627336","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-07","<p>It is Natural England that has a duty under the Habitat Regulations to review any consents/permissions which were issued prior to designation as a European Site. Previously there was discretion as to whether the activities covered by the consents could be tackled through incentives and/or advice rather than formally affirming, modifying or revoking the consent. This discretionary aspect has been removed and under the 2012 amendment of the Habitats Regulations 2010 (Section 23) Natural England now has the legal duty to affirm, modify or revoke any consents issued on European sites, as soon as reasonably practicable.</p><p> </p><p>As part of an England-wide strategy to restore blanket bog to Favourable Conservation Status, Natural England is currently reviewing all consents on blanket bog in line with the duty above (including those which permit burning) and working with landowners to put in place sustainable management and use of these sensitive areas. This will include completing the necessary programme of capital works such as grip-blocking to restore the natural hydrology of the bog and seeding/planting of peat-forming species such as cotton grasses and sphagnum mosses.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Blocking moorland grips (drainage channels) can slow overland flow and reduce the speed at which water enters rivers and streams, especially in small catchments and the upper reaches of larger ones.</p><p> </p><p>Recent research sponsored by Defra shows that restoring moorland habitats can slow overland flow leading to delayed and reduced peak discharge in small catchments. However, it remains difficult to demonstrate the benefits of land use change in larger catchments.</p><p> </p><p>Any upland land management measures introduced to help mitigate flooding need to be considered alongside a full range of other options including hard and soft engineering solutions and other floodplain management options.‎</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-07T13:51:19.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627336/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627336/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Peat Bogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what analysis the Environment Agency has conducted on the condition of blanket bog on moorland currently managed for grouse shooting; and the condition it believes to be optimal for slowing water flows.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","51612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627337","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Department for International Trade is the lead department on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) and has established a process for regular cross-Whitehall engagement with relevant parts of Government, including Defra, to ensure matters arising from the TTIP discussions have been considered appropriately.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","51638 ; 51647","2016-11-10T15:31:18.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627337/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627337/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she has consulted the Office of Water Services on the implications for its remit of the draft Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","51642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627338","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Department for International Trade is the lead department on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) and has established a process for regular cross-Whitehall engagement with relevant parts of Government, including Defra, to ensure matters arising from the TTIP discussions have been considered appropriately.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","51642 ; 51647","2016-11-10T15:31:17.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627338/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627338/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she has consulted the Food Standards Agency on the implications for its remit of the draft Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","51638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627339","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Government is now preparing to negotiate our exit from the European Union. Defra is working with the Department for Exiting the European Union to look at future arrangements including for the UK’s agri-food sector. As part of this, the Government will be working with the devolved administrations, including the Scottish Government, to take their needs and considerations into account as we negotiate and deliver the best possible deal for this country in leaving the European Union.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-08T12:00:30.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627339/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627339/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Agriculture: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to seek access to the EU market under existing terms for Scottish agricultural firms after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","51651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627340","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded the UK remains a full member of the European Union (EU) and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The government has not yet reached a position on the nature of future arrangements once we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-10T14:17:09.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627340/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627340/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Livestock: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to allow individual ports to ban live animal exports after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","51663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627341","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-08","<p>The UK has made no formal assessment of the potential effect of a total ban on domestic ivory sales on the number of elephants poached for ivory. The UK’s proposed ban on trade in modern day, post-1947 ivory, announced by the Secretary of State on 21 September, is a significant step towards implementation of our Manifesto commitment to press for a total ban on ivory sales. It sends a global message of the need to combat the threat to elephants from poaching and puts pressure on other countries to act.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-11-08T12:08:45.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627341/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627341/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-02","Ivory: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 1 November 2016 to Question 50488 and the Answer of 13 October 2016 to Question 47024, whether her Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of the total ban on domestic ivory sales on the number of elephants poached for ivory.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","51733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627343","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>​Somalia is in transition and partway through an electoral process due to culminate with the election of a new President by 30 November. It is vital that the process is transparent, credible and safe; and that commitments to make the process more inclusive, including increasing female representation, are fully respected. The 2016 process is a stepping stone to one person one vote elections scheduled for 2020. It builds on the 2012 process where only 135 elders voted; this year over 14,000 will vote, and the voting will take place beyond Mogadishu.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-07T11:59:43.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627343/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627343/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Somalia: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment the Government has made of whether the ongoing election process in Somalia is free and fair; and if he will take steps to encourage the government of Somalia to increase the number of Somalian people able to vote in that election.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","51742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627344","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>We are concerned by reports of large numbers of arrests in Ethiopia and by restrictions on communication and media usage. We are urging the Government of Ethiopia to respect human rights, and the safeguards around transparency provided for in the Constitution, as it implements the State of Emergency declared on 9 October. We have been clear that continued police repression, and refusal to allow peaceful protest and space for political discussion, will fuel unrest and instability.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-07T12:02:48.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627344/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627344/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Ethiopia: Arrests and Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to address the recent arbitrary arrests and the media shut down in Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","51743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627345","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Prime Minister and the Department for International Trade are currently reviewing the Trade Envoy programme. South Africa remains of critical importance to the UK and is a market with which we continue to have a strong bilateral relationship.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-07T17:41:27.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627345/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627345/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-02","South Africa: Trade Promotion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, when the Government plans to appoint a new trade envoy to South Africa.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","51744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627346","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>President Kabila’s explanation that the delay of Presidential elections is due to the lack of international financial support is incorrect. The primary reason why they are being delayed is the failure of President Kabila and his government to take the necessary steps to deliver elections on time, in accordance with the Democratic Republic of Congo’s constitution and the obligations he has to the Congolese people.</p><p>Independent experts have confirmed that Presidential elections in 2017 are possible. The EU stands ready to provide financial support for a transparent election process based on an inclusive political agreement and a clear timetable approved by stakeholders, provided that all the conditions set out in the Constitution and in UN Security Council Resolution 2277 are met. The UK has earmarked £11.4 million to support the electoral process, which will be disbursed under similar conditions. A number of other nations, including the US, have made similar pledges.</p><p>On 20 September, I made a statement urging the need for a date for Presidential elections in 2017 to be announced as soon as possible; this can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/tobias-ellwood-minister-for-middle-east-and-africa-calls-on-drc-government-to-set-election-date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/tobias-ellwood-minister-for-middle-east-and-africa-calls-on-drc-government-to-set-election-date</a>.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-07T12:06:19.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627346/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627346/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Democratic Republic of Congo: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking in response to President Kabila of Democratic Republic of Congo delaying elections in that county with an explanation that one of the reasons is a lack of EU funding for those elections.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","51746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627347","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-10","<p>We have consulted EU partners on the issue of demolitions. They share our concerns. The EU collectively condemned demolitions in Foreign Affairs Council conclusions on 18 January. The EU has not to date asked for compensation for EU funded infrastructure. No decision has been made yet as to whether to claim compensation in the future.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-10T11:39:57.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627347/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627347/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Occupied Territories: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with other EU member states on demolition of EU-funded buildings in the Occupied Palestinian Territories and compensation for those buildings.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","51713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627348","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>We are unable to provide the specific information requested without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-08T15:01:48.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627348/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627348/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Palestinians: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings there have been in the last 12 months between human rights organisations operating in the Occupied Palestinian Territories and (a) the British Consulate-General in Jerusalem and (b) the British Embassy in Tel Aviv.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","51715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627350","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-10","<p>The FCO has a Temporary Agency worker supply contract with Hays Specialist Recruitment. Records of the FCO's expenditure with them, began in April 2013 and are:</p><table><tbody><tr><td>Financial Year</td><td>(£m)</td></tr><tr><td>FY 13-14</td><td>6.2</td></tr><tr><td>FY 14-15</td><td>4.3</td></tr><tr><td>FY 15-16</td><td>4.7</td></tr><tr><td>FY 16-17 (to end of September 2016)</td><td>2.6</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-11-10T16:46:05.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627350/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627350/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has spent on agency workers in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627351","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>​The total allocation for 2015-16 for both Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) was £7m. It was not separated into individual, distinct budgets as some of our projects and implementing partners delivered simultaneously in both Isreal and the OPTs.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-07T11:52:52.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627351/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627351/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Middle East: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the budget was for projects in (a) Israel and (b) the Palestinian territories within the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund in the 2015-16.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","51682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627352","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) speaks on a regular basis with members of the Gulf Cooperation Council, as well as international partners such as the US and EU Member States, to discuss the full range of security issues in the Middle East.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-07T11:54:45.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627352/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627352/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-02","Middle East: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with (a) the Gulf Cooperation Council and (b) governments of other countries on plans to improve security in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","51710"
